In vivo cardiac function Non-invasive transthoracic echocardiograms were recorded at heart rates of 350–400 beats per minute in rats anaesthetised with 1.5% isoflurane in a mixture of N2O/O2 (1/2, vol/vol) [16] before and 8 weeks after initiation of the diet by an Aloka echo machine (ProSound SSD-4000) using a 13-MHz linear interfaced array transducer. M- and B-mode images were obtained in the parasternal long- and short-axis views of the left ventricle (LV) at mid-papillary level. At end systole (ES) and end diastole (ED), LV lumen diameter (D), LV ventricular diameter (VD) and posterior (PWT) and interventricular septum (IVSWT) wall thicknesses were determined for three cardiac cycles and averaged. The LV dimensions were used to calculate systolic parameters [17]: fractional shortening \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
